WEBVTT

1
00:00:23.690 --> 00:00:26.609
(airplane passing overhead)

2
00:00:56.723 --> 00:00:58.850
You don't like flyin', do you?

3
00:01:00.226 --> 00:01:01.853
What gives you that idea?

4
00:01:04.606 --> 00:01:07.650
You wanna know the secret
to surviving air travel?

5
00:01:09.235 --> 00:01:12.447
After you get where you're going,
take off your shoes and your socks.

6
00:01:12.447 --> 00:01:16.701
Then you walk around on the rug barefoot
and make fists with your toes.

7
00:01:17.994 --> 00:01:19.579
Fists with your toes?

8
00:01:20.246 --> 00:01:22.791
(chuckles) I know, I know.
It sounds crazy.

9
00:01:22.791 --> 00:01:24.709
Trust me.
I've been doin' it for nine years.

10
00:01:24.709 --> 00:01:27.670
Yes, sir. Better than a shower
and a hot cup of coffee.

11
00:01:27.670 --> 00:01:28.922
(chuckles)

12
00:01:28.922 --> 00:01:30.381
Okay.

13
00:01:33.927 --> 00:01:35.929
(passengers chattering)

14
00:01:40.308 --> 00:01:41.935
It's okay. I'm a cop.

15
00:01:44.813 --> 00:01:48.441
Trust me.
I've been doin' this for 11 years.

16
00:01:48.441 --> 00:01:50.944
<i>FLIGHT ATTENDANT (on P.A.): On</i>
<i>behalf of your captain and crew,</i>

17
00:01:50.944 --> 00:01:53.613
<i>we'd like to welcome you to Los Angeles.</i>

18
00:01:53.613 --> 00:01:55.657
<i>Have a very merry Christmas.</i>

19
00:01:57.992 --> 00:01:59.786
(chattering)

20
00:01:59.786 --> 00:02:01.788
♪♪

21
00:02:05.500 --> 00:02:10.755
<i>WOMAN (on P.A.): Flight 247 to Tucson</i>
<i>now boarding at Gate 14.</i>

22
00:02:10.755 --> 00:02:15.301
<i>Flight 247 to Tucson</i>
<i>now boarding at Gate 14.</i>

23
00:02:18.513 --> 00:02:22.517
<i>Mr. Edward Machowski, please report</i>
<i>to the white courtesy phone.</i>

24
00:02:22.517 --> 00:02:25.353
♪♪ (chamber orchestra: classical)

25
00:02:27.897 --> 00:02:29.983
-Ah.
-(speaking Japanese)

26
00:02:29.983 --> 00:02:31.901
How do you do?

27
00:02:35.530 --> 00:02:37.448
♪♪ (continues)

28
00:02:42.370 --> 00:02:44.497
(chattering)

29
00:02:44.497 --> 00:02:48.543
Ladies and gentlemen!
Ladies and gentlemen!

30
00:02:48.543 --> 00:02:51.754
I want to congratulate each and
every one of you for making this one

31
00:02:51.754 --> 00:02:55.508
of the greatest years in the history
of the Nakatomi Corporation.

32
00:02:55.508 --> 00:02:59.137
ALL: (cheering)

33
00:02:59.345 --> 00:03:02.515
On behalf of the chief executive officer,
Mr. Ozu,

34
00:03:02.515 --> 00:03:04.601
and the board of directors,

35
00:03:04.601 --> 00:03:05.894
we thank you, one and all,

36
00:03:05.894 --> 00:03:07.520
and wish you a merry Christmas

37
00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:08.855
and a happy New Year!

38
00:03:08.855 --> 00:03:11.107
-WOMAN: Merry Christmas!
-CROWD: Happy New Year!

39
00:03:12.817 --> 00:03:16.529
Hey, Holly, what about dinner tonight,
huh?

40
00:03:16.529 --> 00:03:18.865
Harry, it's Christmas Eve.

41
00:03:18.865 --> 00:03:21.784
Families, stockings.

42
00:03:23.494 --> 00:03:24.913
Chestnuts.

43
00:03:25.580 --> 00:03:27.498
Rudolph and Frosty.

44
00:03:27.498 --> 00:03:29.584
Any of these things ring a bell?

45
00:03:29.584 --> 00:03:34.380
Actually, I was thinkin' more of
mulled wine, a nice aged Brie

46
00:03:35.006 --> 00:03:36.507
and a roaring fireplace.

47
00:03:36.507 --> 00:03:37.759
You know what I'm sayin'?

48
00:03:38.885 --> 00:03:41.137
(sighs)

49
00:03:41.387 --> 00:03:44.891
Ginny, it's 5:40. Go join the party.
Have some champagne.

50
00:03:44.891 --> 00:03:47.435
You're makin' me feel
like Ebenezer Scrooge.

51
00:03:47.435 --> 00:03:48.603
Thanks a lot, Ms. Gennero.

52
00:03:48.603 --> 00:03:50.897
Do you think the baby
can handle a little sip?

53
00:03:50.897 --> 00:03:53.650
That baby's ready to tend bar.

54
00:03:53.650 --> 00:03:55.902
Last chance.

55
00:03:55.902 --> 00:03:56.986
Bye.

56
00:03:58.821 --> 00:04:00.615
(phone rings)

57
00:04:03.576 --> 00:04:06.788
McClane residence.
Lucy McClane speaking.

58
00:04:06.788 --> 00:04:11.042
Hello, Lucy McClane.
This is your mother speaking.

59
00:04:11.042 --> 00:04:14.504
<i>Mommy! When are you</i>
<i>coming home?</i>

60
00:04:14.504 --> 00:04:18.716
Pretty soon. Pretty soon.
You'll be in bed when I get there though.

61
00:04:18.716 --> 00:04:21.135
Let me talk to Paulina, okay, hon?

62
00:04:21.427 --> 00:04:25.515
And no snoopin' around the house
looking for presents.

63
00:04:25.515 --> 00:04:27.850
Is Daddy coming home with you?

64
00:04:30.103 --> 00:04:34.023
Well, we'll see what
Santa and Mommy can do, okay?

65
00:04:34.023 --> 00:04:36.901
Put Paulina on. Bye, honey.

66
00:04:36.901 --> 00:04:38.194
<i>LUCY: Paulina!</i>

67
00:04:43.074 --> 00:04:45.493
Hola, Mrs. Holly.

68
00:04:45.493 --> 00:04:48.663
Um, did Mr. McClane call?

69
00:04:48.663 --> 00:04:52.166
<i>No, Mrs. Holly. No </i>telefonó.

70
00:04:52.417 --> 00:04:55.586
Well, he probably just didn't
have time before his flight.

71
00:04:55.586 --> 00:04:59.549
Um, it might be a good idea to make up
the spare bedroom just in case.

72
00:04:59.549 --> 00:05:02.218
<i>Sí, </i>Mrs. Holly. I do that already.

73
00:05:02.218 --> 00:05:04.679
What would I do without you, Paulina?

74
00:05:25.658 --> 00:05:27.618
(squeals)

75
00:05:30.830 --> 00:05:31.956
California.

76
00:05:42.675 --> 00:05:44.802
Excuse me.

77
00:05:44.802 --> 00:05:46.846
Hey, I'm John McClane.

78
00:05:46.846 --> 00:05:49.682
Argyle. I'm your limo driver.

79
00:05:52.018 --> 00:05:54.062
Nice bear.

80
00:05:58.524 --> 00:06:01.694
Okay, Argyle.

81
00:06:01.694 --> 00:06:02.862
What do we do now?

82
00:06:02.862 --> 00:06:05.198
I was, uh, hopin' you could tell me.

83
00:06:05.198 --> 00:06:07.742
It's my first time drivin' a limo.

84
00:06:07.742 --> 00:06:10.828
Oh, that's okay.
It's my first time ridin' in one.

85
00:06:10.828 --> 00:06:13.831
Relax. We got everything in this mug, man.

86
00:06:13.831 --> 00:06:17.210
Look at this-- CD, C.B., TV,

87
00:06:17.210 --> 00:06:21.214
telephone, full bar, VHS. (laughs)

88
00:06:21.214 --> 00:06:24.842
If your friend's hot to trot, I know
a few mama bears we can hook up with.

89
00:06:24.842 --> 00:06:26.803
(chuckles)

90
00:06:27.220 --> 00:06:29.889
-Or is he married?
-He's married.

91
00:06:29.889 --> 00:06:31.140
Okay.

92
00:06:33.059 --> 00:06:35.895
Oh, sorry about that.
It's the girl's day off.

93
00:06:35.895 --> 00:06:38.022
I didn't know you were gonna sit up front.

94
00:06:38.856 --> 00:06:40.900
So, uh, your lady live out here?

95
00:06:40.900 --> 00:06:43.027
About the past six months.

96
00:06:43.027 --> 00:06:46.072
Meaning you still live in New York.

97
00:06:46.072 --> 00:06:48.241
You always ask this many questions,
Argyle?

98
00:06:48.241 --> 00:06:49.617
(chuckles)

99
00:06:49.617 --> 00:06:53.663
Sorry, man. I used to drive a cab, and,
uh, people would expect a little chitchat.

100
00:06:54.288 --> 00:06:55.832
So, you divorced?

101
00:06:55.832 --> 00:06:57.667
Just drive the car, man.

102
00:06:57.667 --> 00:07:01.295
Hey, come on. You divorced?
You separated? She beat you up?

103
00:07:01.546 --> 00:07:02.922
(laughing)

104
00:07:04.757 --> 00:07:06.342
She had a good job.

105
00:07:06.342 --> 00:07:08.302
Turned into a great career.

106
00:07:08.302 --> 00:07:10.346
Ah, that meant she had to move here.

107
00:07:11.180 --> 00:07:13.266
You're very fast, Argyle.

108
00:07:13.558 --> 00:07:15.977
So why didn't you come?

109
00:07:18.855 --> 00:07:20.982
Well, why didn't you come with her, man?
What's up?

110
00:07:22.358 --> 00:07:23.943
'Cause I'm a New York cop.

111
00:07:24.610 --> 00:07:26.779
I got a six-month backlog
of New York scumbags

112
00:07:26.779 --> 00:07:28.239
I'm still trying to put behind bars.

113
00:07:28.239 --> 00:07:30.241
I can't just pick up and go that easy.

114
00:07:30.241 --> 00:07:32.285
In other words, you thought
she wasn't gonna make it out here,

115
00:07:32.285 --> 00:07:33.828
and she'd come crawling on back to you,

116
00:07:33.828 --> 00:07:36.372
so why bother to pack, right? (laughs)

117
00:07:37.748 --> 00:07:40.668
Like I said, you're very fast, Argyle.

118
00:07:40.668 --> 00:07:41.919
You mind if we hear some tunes?

119
00:07:45.131 --> 00:07:47.216
<i>-♪♪ (rap)</i>
-Hey, that'll work.

120
00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:51.971
Don't you got any Christmas music?

121
00:07:51.971 --> 00:07:54.307
ARGYLE: This is Christmas music.

122
00:07:56.309 --> 00:07:58.978
<i>♪ It was December 24th</i>
<i>on Hollis Ave. after dark ♪</i>

123
00:07:58.978 --> 00:08:01.772
<i>♪ When I see a man chillin'</i>
<i>with his dog in the park ♪</i>

124
00:08:01.772 --> 00:08:03.900
<i>♪ I approached him very slowly</i>
<i>with my heart full of fear ♪</i>

125
00:08:03.900 --> 00:08:06.819
<i>♪ Looked at his dog</i>
<i>Oh, my God, a ill reindeer ♪</i>

126
00:08:06.819 --> 00:08:09.071
<i>♪ But then I was illin'</i>
<i>'cause the man had a beard ♪</i>

127
00:08:09.071 --> 00:08:11.824
<i>♪ And a bag full of goodies</i>
<i>12:00 had neared ♪</i>

128
00:08:11.824 --> 00:08:14.202
<i>♪ So I turned my head a second</i>
<i>and the man was gone ♪</i>

129
00:08:14.202 --> 00:08:16.787
<i>♪ But he must have dropped his wallet</i>
<i>smack down on the lawn ♪</i>

130
00:08:16.787 --> 00:08:19.165
<i>♪ I picked the wallet up</i>
<i>and then I took a pause ♪</i>

131
00:08:19.165 --> 00:08:21.834
<i>♪ Took out the license and</i>
<i>it cold said "Santa Claus" ♪</i>

132
00:08:21.834 --> 00:08:23.878
<i>♪ A million dollars in it</i>
<i>Cold hundreds of G's ♪</i>

133
00:08:23.878 --> 00:08:25.379
So your lady sees you,

134
00:08:25.379 --> 00:08:27.465
you run into each other's arms,
the music comes up,

135
00:08:27.465 --> 00:08:30.134
and you live happily ever after, right?

136
00:08:30.134 --> 00:08:31.844
I can live with that.

137
00:08:33.262 --> 00:08:35.890
So if it doesn't work out, man,
you got a place to stay?

138
00:08:36.891 --> 00:08:38.726
I'll find a place.

139
00:08:39.852 --> 00:08:43.022
I tell you what. I'm gonna pull in
the parking garage, and I'll wait.

140
00:08:43.022 --> 00:08:45.149
You score, you give me a call
on the car phone.

141
00:08:45.775 --> 00:08:47.276
I'll take your bags to the desk.

142
00:08:47.276 --> 00:08:49.028
You strike out, I'll get you a hotel.

143
00:08:50.071 --> 00:08:51.948
You're all right, Argyle.

144
00:08:51.948 --> 00:08:54.659
Just remember that
when you sign for the tip.

145
00:09:17.932 --> 00:09:20.101
Hi.

146
00:09:20.101 --> 00:09:22.895
-Good evening.
-I'm here to see Holly McClane.

147
00:09:22.895 --> 00:09:24.772
Just type it in there.

148
00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:29.986
(beeping)

149
00:09:30.736 --> 00:09:32.238
Cute toy.

150
00:09:32.822 --> 00:09:35.741
Yeah. You have to take a leak,
it'll even help you find your zipper.

151
00:09:39.412 --> 00:09:41.372
(beeping)

152
00:09:45.376 --> 00:09:47.295
(beeping)

153
00:09:51.882 --> 00:09:53.801
Christ.

154
00:09:55.845 --> 00:09:58.431
(beeping)

155
00:09:59.098 --> 00:10:00.850
McCLANE: Thirtieth floor.

156
00:10:00.850 --> 00:10:03.853
The party. They're the only ones
left in the building.

157
00:10:03.853 --> 00:10:07.356
Take the express elevator.
Get off where you hear the noise.

158
00:10:07.356 --> 00:10:09.483
Thanks.

159
00:10:09.483 --> 00:10:11.485
(beeps)

160
00:10:11.777 --> 00:10:14.989
♪♪ (whistling "Jingle Bells")

161
00:10:36.093 --> 00:10:38.179
(dings)

162
00:10:55.029 --> 00:10:57.948
PEOPLE (laughing, chattering)

163
00:11:01.118 --> 00:11:03.954
♪♪ (chamber orchestra: classical)

164
00:11:06.999 --> 00:11:09.377
-Champagne, sir?
-Yeah. Thanks.

165
00:11:39.865 --> 00:11:41.575
♪♪ (continues)

166
00:11:44.412 --> 00:11:45.621
Oh, I'm sorry.

167
00:11:46.539 --> 00:11:49.166
Hey! Merry Christmas!

168
00:11:52.253 --> 00:11:54.588
Jesus.

169
00:11:54.588 --> 00:11:57.091
Fuckin' California.

170
00:11:57.091 --> 00:11:59.260
I couldn't agree with you more.

171
00:11:59.260 --> 00:12:01.095
Why don't I talk to him right now?

172
00:12:02.221 --> 00:12:05.057
Hi. I'm looking for, uh--

173
00:12:05.057 --> 00:12:06.434
-Holly Gennero.
-Yeah.

174
00:12:06.434 --> 00:12:08.227
Then you must be John McClane.

175
00:12:08.227 --> 00:12:09.645
-Joe Takagi.
-Hi.

176
00:12:09.645 --> 00:12:12.064
-How was your ride in?
-Nice.

177
00:12:12.064 --> 00:12:15.109
-I have you to thank for that?
-It seemed the least we could do.

178
00:12:15.484 --> 00:12:17.194
It's quite a place you have here.

179
00:12:17.194 --> 00:12:19.238
It will be if we ever get it finished.

180
00:12:19.238 --> 00:12:21.532
There are still several floors
under construction.

181
00:12:21.532 --> 00:12:25.035
Holly went to the vault room to fax some
documents. She should be back any minute.

182
00:12:25.411 --> 00:12:27.329
In the meanwhile,
her office is right back here.

183
00:12:29.874 --> 00:12:32.001
-(man sniffs)
-Ellis.

184
00:12:32.001 --> 00:12:34.211
(sniffs)

185
00:12:34.211 --> 00:12:37.256
I was just makin' a call,
and this was, uh, the nearest phone.

186
00:12:37.256 --> 00:12:40.926
I want you to meet John McClane,
Holly's husband.

187
00:12:42.219 --> 00:12:43.637
Holly's policeman.

188
00:12:43.637 --> 00:12:46.056
Ellis is in charge of
international development.

189
00:12:46.056 --> 00:12:48.225
(sniffs) Heard a heck of a lot about you.

190
00:12:48.225 --> 00:12:50.436
Missed some.

191
00:12:50.436 --> 00:12:52.563
(sniffs)

192
00:12:52.563 --> 00:12:53.606
Uh, could I get you anything?

193
00:12:53.606 --> 00:12:55.149
Food, cake, uh,

194
00:12:55.149 --> 00:12:57.109
some watered-down champagne?

195
00:12:57.109 --> 00:12:58.652
No, thank you. I'm fine.

196
00:13:00.154 --> 00:13:03.240
You throw quite a party.

197
00:13:03.240 --> 00:13:06.118
I didn't realize they celebrated Christmas
in Japan.

198
00:13:06.118 --> 00:13:07.578
Hey, we're flexible.

199
00:13:07.578 --> 00:13:10.331
Pearl Harbor didn't work out,
so we got you with tape decks.

200
00:13:10.331 --> 00:13:13.334
(laughing)

201
00:13:13.334 --> 00:13:15.669
Actually, it's kind of sort of
a double celebration.

202
00:13:15.920 --> 00:13:17.588
We, uh, closed a pretty big deal today.

203
00:13:17.588 --> 00:13:20.132
And a lot of it was due to Holly.
Am I right, Jo-Jo?

204
00:13:20.132 --> 00:13:23.469
-Go without me. I'll be four minutes.
-(laughs, sniffs)

205
00:13:26.639 --> 00:13:28.474
John.

206
00:13:31.644 --> 00:13:34.021
Have you met everyone?

207
00:13:34.021 --> 00:13:36.148
No, we've been sticking him with spears.

208
00:13:36.148 --> 00:13:38.484
Of course he has.

209
00:13:38.484 --> 00:13:41.153
She was made for the business.
Tough as nails.

210
00:13:41.153 --> 00:13:45.074
-Yeah.
-I was hoping you made that flight.

211
00:13:45.074 --> 00:13:47.701
Show him the watch. (sniffs)

212
00:13:47.701 --> 00:13:49.036
Later.

213
00:13:49.036 --> 00:13:51.121
Well, go on. Show him.
What, are you embarrassed?

214
00:13:51.121 --> 00:13:54.166
It's just a small token of appreciation
for all her hard work.

215
00:13:55.167 --> 00:13:56.335
It's a Rolex.

216
00:13:57.378 --> 00:13:59.338
I'm sure I'll see it later.

217
00:13:59.338 --> 00:14:01.590
Is there a place where I could wash up?

218
00:14:01.590 --> 00:14:04.093
Sure.

219
00:14:19.400 --> 00:14:21.151
You'll have to forgive Ellis.

220
00:14:21.151 --> 00:14:24.321
He gets very depressed this time of year.

221
00:14:24.321 --> 00:14:27.032
He thought he was God's greatest gift,
you know?

222
00:14:27.032 --> 00:14:29.285
Yeah, I know the type.

223
00:14:29.285 --> 00:14:31.412
I think he's got his eye on you.

224
00:14:32.496 --> 00:14:35.374
It's okay. I have my eye
on his private bathroom.

225
00:14:36.375 --> 00:14:38.669
Where you staying?

226
00:14:38.669 --> 00:14:42.631
Things happened so fast, I didn't get
a chance to ask you on the phone.

227
00:14:42.631 --> 00:14:46.719
-Cappy Roberts retired out here.
-Oh, yeah?

228
00:14:46.719 --> 00:14:49.555
-Told me I could bunk in with him.
-Cappy retired, huh?

229
00:14:49.555 --> 00:14:51.765
-Where's he live?
-Ramona.

230
00:14:51.765 --> 00:14:53.809
(laughs) Pomona.

231
00:14:54.101 --> 00:14:56.520
-Huh?
-Pomona. (chuckles)

232
00:14:56.520 --> 00:14:59.523
-Pomona.
-Yeah. (chuckles)

233
00:14:59.523 --> 00:15:01.525
God, you'll be in the car half the time.

234
00:15:03.360 --> 00:15:06.697
Why don't we make it easy?
I have a spare bedroom.

235
00:15:06.697 --> 00:15:09.575
I mean, it's not huge or anything,

236
00:15:09.575 --> 00:15:11.452
but the kids would love
to have you at the house.

237
00:15:14.079 --> 00:15:15.539
They would, huh?

238
00:15:19.084 --> 00:15:20.544
I would too.

239
00:15:21.462 --> 00:15:23.797
Oh! Ooh!

240
00:15:23.797 --> 00:15:26.091
Sorry.

241
00:15:28.677 --> 00:15:30.638
(door closes)

242
00:15:33.098 --> 00:15:35.517
I missed you.

243
00:15:42.149 --> 00:15:44.151
I guess you didn't miss my name,
though, huh?

244
00:15:45.277 --> 00:15:48.238
Except maybe when you're signing checks?

245
00:15:48.238 --> 00:15:50.240
Since when did you start
using "Ms. Gennero"?

246
00:15:51.325 --> 00:15:53.661
(sighs)

247
00:15:53.661 --> 00:15:55.621
This is a Japanese company.

248
00:15:55.621 --> 00:15:57.873
They figure a married woman's
got one foot--

249
00:15:57.873 --> 00:15:59.583
You are a married woman, Holly.
You're married to me.

250
00:15:59.583 --> 00:16:01.794
I'm not gonna have this conversation
again. We did this in July.

251
00:16:02.127 --> 00:16:04.338
-We never finished this conversation.
-I had an opportunity.

252
00:16:04.338 --> 00:16:06.674
-I had to take it.
-Right. No matter what the consequences,

253
00:16:06.674 --> 00:16:09.635
no matter what it did to our marriage,
you had to.

254
00:16:09.635 --> 00:16:11.887
It didn't do anything except change your
idea of what our marriage should be.

255
00:16:11.887 --> 00:16:14.890
I don't think you have a clue what my idea
of our marriage should be.

256
00:16:14.890 --> 00:16:16.892
I know exactly what your idea
of our marriage should be.

257
00:16:17.142 --> 00:16:18.560
-(knocking)
-Ms. Gennero, I--

258
00:16:21.146 --> 00:16:24.566
-Excuse me.
-Hi.

259
00:16:25.776 --> 00:16:27.903
Um, Mr. Takagi is looking for you.

260
00:16:28.153 --> 00:16:30.447
He-- He wants you to say something
to the troops.

261
00:16:30.447 --> 00:16:31.490
Thank you.

262
00:16:36.161 --> 00:16:39.456
Speech time. Be back in a few minutes.

263
00:16:40.624 --> 00:16:43.627
(door opens, closes)

264
00:16:47.548 --> 00:16:49.675
(sighs)

265
00:16:51.677 --> 00:16:53.887
That's great, John.

266
00:16:53.887 --> 00:16:56.265
Good job. Very mature.

267
00:17:03.188 --> 00:17:04.815
(tires squealing)

268
00:17:46.315 --> 00:17:49.443
So Kareem rebounds, right?
Feeds Worthy on the break.

269
00:17:49.443 --> 00:17:51.570
Over to A.C., to Magic,

270
00:17:51.570 --> 00:17:53.906
then back to Worthy, right?

271
00:17:53.906 --> 00:17:56.533
Boom! Two points.

272
00:17:57.409 --> 00:17:58.494
(grunts)

273
00:18:00.204 --> 00:18:01.288
We're in.

274
00:18:14.259 --> 00:18:16.011
♪♪ (humming)

275
00:18:34.571 --> 00:18:36.240
(groans)

276
00:19:02.432 --> 00:19:03.976
♪♪ (humming continues)

277
00:19:05.811 --> 00:19:07.855
(beeping)

278
00:19:11.608 --> 00:19:12.985
(beeping)

279
00:19:26.790 --> 00:19:28.417
(typing)

280
00:19:54.484 --> 00:19:56.486
♪♪ (vocalizing)

281
00:20:12.419 --> 00:20:14.630
(beeping)

282
00:20:30.896 --> 00:20:32.814
(speaking German)

283
00:20:48.080 --> 00:20:49.915
(whirring)

284
00:21:08.058 --> 00:21:10.769
Son of a bitch.

285
00:21:10.769 --> 00:21:12.938
(chuckles)

286
00:21:12.938 --> 00:21:14.856
Fists with your toes.

287
00:21:32.582 --> 00:21:33.709
(beeps)

288
00:21:41.717 --> 00:21:43.927
(dialing)

289
00:21:43.927 --> 00:21:46.096
(line ringing)

290
00:21:46.096 --> 00:21:47.764
-♪♪ (car stereo blaring)
-Yeah, Argyle.

291
00:21:47.764 --> 00:21:49.683
<i>ARGYLE: Hey, Mac!</i>
<i>How's it goin' up there?</i>

292
00:21:49.683 --> 00:21:51.143
Oh, all right. Where are you?

293
00:21:51.143 --> 00:21:54.187
I'm kickin' it in the garage. What's
the word with you and your lady, man?

294
00:21:54.187 --> 00:21:56.565
Uh, the vote's not in yet.

295
00:21:58.817 --> 00:21:59.776
(beeps)

296
00:21:59.776 --> 00:22:01.611
♪♪ (humming)

297
00:22:05.490 --> 00:22:07.784
-(German)
-MAN (speaking German)

298
00:22:07.784 --> 00:22:09.661
-(chainsaw starts)
-(shouting in German)

299
00:22:28.180 --> 00:22:29.598
Argyle?

300
00:22:29.598 --> 00:22:32.184
-♪♪ (continues)
-Mac, you there? Hello?

301
00:22:32.184 --> 00:22:34.728
♪♪ (humming)

302
00:22:41.193 --> 00:22:42.944
You know the number. Use it!

303
00:22:54.164 --> 00:22:55.999
♪♪ (chamber orchestra: classical)

304
00:23:07.719 --> 00:23:09.721
(machine gun fire)

305
00:23:09.721 --> 00:23:11.848
WOMAN: (screams)

306
00:23:11.848 --> 00:23:14.601
-(gunfire)
-(crowd screaming)

307
00:23:17.729 --> 00:23:19.856
(shouts in German)

308
00:23:19.856 --> 00:23:21.942
(gunfire continues)

309
00:23:25.070 --> 00:23:26.905
(shouts in German)

310
00:23:31.284 --> 00:23:33.120
WOMAN: (screaming)

311
00:23:36.957 --> 00:23:38.917
(German)

312
00:23:42.546 --> 00:23:44.172
(gunfire continues)

313
00:23:51.763 --> 00:23:54.766
BOTH (speak German)

314
00:23:54.766 --> 00:23:56.101
(laughs)

315
00:24:08.780 --> 00:24:10.949
-CROWD: (screaming)
-(gunfire)

316
00:24:15.036 --> 00:24:17.122
Stay calm. Everything's gonna be fine.

317
00:24:18.081 --> 00:24:19.833
Everything's gonna be fine.

318
00:24:38.810 --> 00:24:39.978
Shit!

319
00:24:43.940 --> 00:24:46.276
Think. Think.

320
00:24:54.201 --> 00:24:56.077
CROWD: (screaming)

321
00:25:02.959 --> 00:25:05.128
Ladies and gentlemen.

322
00:25:07.214 --> 00:25:08.840
Ladies and gentlemen.

323
00:25:16.056 --> 00:25:20.227
"Due to the Nakatomi Corporation's legacy
of greed around the globe,

324
00:25:20.227 --> 00:25:24.231
they're about to be taught a lesson
in the real use of power.

325
00:25:25.815 --> 00:25:27.651
You will be witnesses."

326
00:25:29.819 --> 00:25:31.905
Now...

327
00:25:31.905 --> 00:25:33.990
where is Mr. Takagi?

328
00:25:36.785 --> 00:25:39.829
Joseph Yoshinobu Takagi.

329
00:25:41.289 --> 00:25:43.833
Born, Kyoto, 1937.

330
00:25:43.833 --> 00:25:45.377
(whispers) Don't move.

331
00:25:45.877 --> 00:25:50.006
Family emigrated to San Pedro,
California, 1939.

332
00:25:51.258 --> 00:25:55.804
Interned at Manzanar, 1942 to '43.

333
00:25:57.138 --> 00:26:00.767
Scholarship student,
University of California,

334
00:26:00.767 --> 00:26:02.811
1955.

335
00:26:06.898 --> 00:26:11.778
Law degree, Stanford, 1962.

336
00:26:11.778 --> 00:26:15.156
M.B.A., Harvard, 1970.

337
00:26:16.408 --> 00:26:19.202
President, Nakatomi Trading.

338
00:26:19.202 --> 00:26:22.080
Vice Chairman, Nakatomi Investment Group.

339
00:26:22.080 --> 00:26:23.373
Enough.

340
00:26:24.708 --> 00:26:27.919
And father of five.

341
00:26:28.461 --> 00:26:30.130
I am Takagi.

342
00:26:31.339 --> 00:26:33.425
How do you do?

343
00:26:33.758 --> 00:26:35.969
It's a pleasure to meet you.

344
00:26:35.969 --> 00:26:37.721
CROWD: (gasping)

345
00:26:40.890 --> 00:26:42.517
(computer beeping)

346
00:26:48.231 --> 00:26:51.276
Computers. Thirty-two, construction.
Thirty-three, computers.

347
00:26:52.193 --> 00:26:55.113
♪♪ HANS (humming)

348
00:27:04.831 --> 00:27:06.166
Nice suit.

349
00:27:07.125 --> 00:27:08.960
John Philips, London.

350
00:27:11.421 --> 00:27:13.965
I have two myself.

351
00:27:13.965 --> 00:27:16.801
Rumor has it Arafat buys his there.

352
00:27:19.471 --> 00:27:21.514
(speaking Italian)

353
00:27:21.765 --> 00:27:24.142
-In there?
-On the left. On the left.

354
00:27:24.142 --> 00:27:26.061
(Italian)

355
00:27:34.819 --> 00:27:36.988
♪♪ (humming)

356
00:27:46.956 --> 00:27:51.503
"And when Alexander saw the breadth
of his domain, he wept,

357
00:27:51.503 --> 00:27:54.506
for there were no more worlds to conquer."

358
00:27:56.216 --> 00:27:59.052
(chuckling)

359
00:27:59.052 --> 00:28:01.429
Benefits of a classical education.

360
00:28:02.555 --> 00:28:06.101
Oh, that's beautiful.

361
00:28:07.894 --> 00:28:10.939
I always enjoyed to make models
when I was a boy.

362
00:28:10.939 --> 00:28:15.944
The exactness, the attention
to every conceivable detail.

363
00:28:15.944 --> 00:28:18.113
It's beautiful.

364
00:28:18.113 --> 00:28:21.032
Is this what this is all about?
Our project in Indonesia?

365
00:28:22.867 --> 00:28:24.994
TAKAGI: Contrary to what you people
may think,

366
00:28:24.994 --> 00:28:28.289
we're going to develop that region,
not exploit it.

367
00:28:28.289 --> 00:28:29.916
HANS: I believe you.

368
00:28:30.458 --> 00:28:33.294
I read the article in<i> Forbes.</i>

369
00:28:35.046 --> 00:28:36.548
Mr. Takagi.

370
00:28:38.383 --> 00:28:41.428
I could talk about industrialization
and men's fashions all day,

371
00:28:41.428 --> 00:28:43.596
but I'm afraid work must intrude,

372
00:28:43.596 --> 00:28:48.059
and my associate, Theo,
has some questions for you.

373
00:28:48.059 --> 00:28:51.271
Sort of fill-in-the-blanks questions,
actually.

374
00:28:51.271 --> 00:28:53.064
(beeping)

375
00:29:00.530 --> 00:29:02.323
I don't have that code.

376
00:29:03.616 --> 00:29:06.536
You broke in here to access our computer?

377
00:29:07.036 --> 00:29:08.455
Any information you could get,

378
00:29:08.455 --> 00:29:10.457
when they wake up in Tokyo in the morning,
they'll change it.

379
00:29:10.457 --> 00:29:13.042
You won't be able to blackmail
our executives, threaten our profit--

380
00:29:13.042 --> 00:29:15.420
Sit down!

381
00:29:25.263 --> 00:29:29.142
Mr. Takagi, I'm really not interested
in your computer.

382
00:29:34.147 --> 00:29:36.483
But I need the code key

383
00:29:36.483 --> 00:29:38.526
because I am interested

384
00:29:38.526 --> 00:29:41.279
in the $640 million

385
00:29:41.279 --> 00:29:42.989
in negotiable bearer bonds

386
00:29:42.989 --> 00:29:45.617
that you have locked in your vault.

387
00:29:45.617 --> 00:29:49.454
And the computer controls the vault.

388
00:29:50.455 --> 00:29:53.041
You want money?

389
00:29:53.041 --> 00:29:55.460
What kind of terrorists are you?

390
00:29:55.460 --> 00:29:57.337
(chuckling)

391
00:29:58.588 --> 00:30:01.341
Who said we were terrorists?

392
00:30:01.341 --> 00:30:03.301
(chuckling continues)

393
00:30:09.182 --> 00:30:12.727
Mr. Takagi, I sympathize
with your reluctance,

394
00:30:12.977 --> 00:30:17.482
but I'm sure you realize you're not
dealing with anything significant here.

395
00:30:17.482 --> 00:30:20.485
It's not as if
it's the education of your children.

396
00:30:20.485 --> 00:30:23.446
The bonds represent, at most,

397
00:30:23.446 --> 00:30:27.033
ten days operating capital
for your parent organization.

398
00:30:27.033 --> 00:30:29.702
It's really no more than
a temporary inconvenience.

399
00:30:29.702 --> 00:30:31.663
Now...

400
00:30:36.125 --> 00:30:38.211
the code, please.

401
00:30:39.504 --> 00:30:41.214
It's useless to you.

402
00:30:41.214 --> 00:30:44.175
There are seven safeguards on our vault,
and the code key is only one of them.

403
00:30:44.175 --> 00:30:45.426
You'll never get it open.

404
00:30:45.426 --> 00:30:48.137
Then there's no reason
not to tell it to us.

405
00:30:49.013 --> 00:30:50.306
I told you.

406
00:30:50.306 --> 00:30:52.433
It's not over yet.

407
00:30:57.188 --> 00:31:00.525
That's a very nice suit, Mr. Takagi.

408
00:31:01.234 --> 00:31:03.444
It would be a shame to ruin it.

409
00:31:07.156 --> 00:31:09.701
I'm going to count to three.

410
00:31:10.702 --> 00:31:13.329
There will not be a four.

411
00:31:13.329 --> 00:31:16.291
Give me the code.

412
00:31:17.458 --> 00:31:18.668
One.

413
00:31:21.671 --> 00:31:23.131
Two.

414
00:31:25.174 --> 00:31:27.218
-Three.
-TAGAKI: I don't know it. I'm telling you.

415
00:31:27.218 --> 00:31:29.637
Get on a jet to Tokyo to ask the chairman.

416
00:31:29.637 --> 00:31:31.723
I'm telling you,
you're just gonna have to kill me.

417
00:31:32.307 --> 00:31:33.182
Okay.

418
00:31:37.228 --> 00:31:38.771
We'll do it the hard way.

419
00:31:39.063 --> 00:31:40.690
Tony, see if you can dispose of that.

420
00:31:40.690 --> 00:31:44.235
Karl, you'd better go and check on
Heinrich's work up on the machine floor.

421
00:31:44.235 --> 00:31:46.154
-(table rattles)
-(grunts)

422
00:32:09.260 --> 00:32:10.553
Nothing.

423
00:32:10.553 --> 00:32:12.430
See to Heinrich.

424
00:32:14.432 --> 00:32:19.479
Now, you can break the code?

425
00:32:19.479 --> 00:32:22.565
You didn't bring me along
for my charming personality.

426
00:32:29.113 --> 00:32:33.743
Argyle, tell me you heard the shots
and you're callin' the police right now.

427
00:32:33.743 --> 00:32:36.204
-♪♪ (stereo blaring)
-Of course I'm still comin' by later.

428
00:32:37.538 --> 00:32:40.249
Sweetheart, have I ever lied to you?

429
00:32:40.249 --> 00:32:42.752
My boss? He thinks
I'm on my way to Vegas.

430
00:32:44.170 --> 00:32:45.797
Uli, get up on the pipes.

431
00:32:47.340 --> 00:32:49.592
Marco, you go through here.

432
00:32:51.678 --> 00:32:53.638
-I'll throw you the cord.
-Yeah.

433
00:32:57.725 --> 00:32:58.726
Hans, we're on the roof.

434
00:33:11.572 --> 00:33:13.533
Here.

435
00:33:16.661 --> 00:33:18.663
Uli!

436
00:33:25.461 --> 00:33:30.258
Thirty minutes to break the code.
Two hours, two-and-a-half hours,

437
00:33:30.258 --> 00:33:32.802
for the five mechanicals, at the minimum.

438
00:33:32.802 --> 00:33:35.430
The seventh lock, however,
is out of my hands.

439
00:33:35.430 --> 00:33:37.390
(beeping)

440
00:33:52.822 --> 00:33:54.699
(beeping)

441
00:33:58.494 --> 00:34:00.955
-I'm sorry.
-The seventh lock.

442
00:34:00.955 --> 00:34:03.416
The electromagnetic seal.

443
00:34:03.416 --> 00:34:05.752
You do understand the circuits
cannot be cut locally.

444
00:34:07.420 --> 00:34:09.630
Trust me.

445
00:34:10.631 --> 00:34:12.675
Why the fuck didn't you stop 'em, John?

446
00:34:14.510 --> 00:34:16.721
'Cause then you'd be dead too, asshole.

447
00:34:17.847 --> 00:34:19.515
Think, goddamn it. Think!

448
00:34:28.858 --> 00:34:30.318
(beeping)

449
00:34:31.694 --> 00:34:33.863
We've got a fire alarm.

450
00:34:33.863 --> 00:34:35.948
Call 911.

451
00:34:35.948 --> 00:34:37.492
Give them the guard's name,

452
00:34:37.492 --> 00:34:40.328
the building code number
and cancel the alarm.

453
00:34:40.328 --> 00:34:42.455
Then disable the system.

454
00:34:44.874 --> 00:34:47.835
Eddie, on what floor did the alarm go off?

455
00:34:49.212 --> 00:34:51.422
Now? Should we go?

456
00:34:51.714 --> 00:34:52.590
<i>Nein.</i>

457
00:34:58.930 --> 00:35:00.681
(sirens wailing)

458
00:35:03.810 --> 00:35:07.480
Yes. Oh, baby, come to papa. Come on.

459
00:35:08.606 --> 00:35:10.733
Ah! (laughs)

460
00:35:12.693 --> 00:35:15.863
Baby. Come on, baby. Come on, baby.

461
00:35:15.863 --> 00:35:18.407
Come to papa.
I'll kiss your fuckin' Dalmatian.

462
00:35:21.786 --> 00:35:24.747
Oh, you stupid motherfuckers!
No! No!

463
00:35:24.747 --> 00:35:27.500
Turn the fuckin' truck around!

464
00:35:27.500 --> 00:35:28.626
(elevator bell dings)

465
00:36:00.366 --> 00:36:03.494
The fire has been called off, my friend.

466
00:36:08.708 --> 00:36:09.959
No one is coming to help you.

467
00:36:14.380 --> 00:36:17.675
You might as well come out
and join the others.

468
00:36:20.344 --> 00:36:22.513
I promise I won't hurt you.

469
00:36:29.395 --> 00:36:31.647
(power saw whirring)

470
00:36:51.542 --> 00:36:54.420
Drop it, dickhead. It's the police.

471
00:36:55.463 --> 00:36:57.006
You won't hurt me.

472
00:36:57.006 --> 00:36:59.133
Oh, yeah? Why not?

473
00:36:59.342 --> 00:37:01.052
Because you're a policeman.

474
00:37:01.052 --> 00:37:03.512
There are rules for policemen.

475
00:37:03.512 --> 00:37:06.891
Yeah. That's what my captain
keeps tellin' me.

476
00:37:14.148 --> 00:37:15.733
(grunts)

477
00:37:18.069 --> 00:37:20.154
Drop that, motherfucker!
I'll fuckin' kill you!

478
00:37:20.154 --> 00:37:22.073
(grunting)

479
00:37:26.410 --> 00:37:28.746
Come on! Come on!
I'll fuckin' rip your head off!

480
00:37:33.376 --> 00:37:35.127
(groans)

481
00:37:39.799 --> 00:37:41.050
(grunts)

482
00:38:01.112 --> 00:38:02.613
(beeping)

483
00:38:09.078 --> 00:38:10.997
(beeping)

484
00:38:13.040 --> 00:38:15.793
You bet your ass I wish to proceed.

485
00:38:17.128 --> 00:38:18.587
(whirring)

486
00:38:56.167 --> 00:38:57.877
Nine million terrorists in the world,

487
00:38:57.877 --> 00:39:00.129
and I gotta kill one
with feet smaller than my sister.

488
00:39:50.888 --> 00:39:54.016
I wanted this to be professional,

489
00:39:54.016 --> 00:39:55.267
efficient, adult, cooperative.

490
00:39:55.518 --> 00:39:57.228
Not a lot to ask.

491
00:39:57.228 --> 00:39:59.605
Alas, your Mr. Takagi
did not see it that way,

492
00:39:59.605 --> 00:40:03.234
so he won't be joining us
for the rest of his life.

493
00:40:05.069 --> 00:40:08.239
So we can go any way you want us.

494
00:40:08.572 --> 00:40:11.617
You can walk out of here
or be carried out.

495
00:40:11.617 --> 00:40:15.538
But have no illusions. We are in charge.

496
00:40:16.914 --> 00:40:19.333
So, decide now, each of you.

497
00:40:20.751 --> 00:40:22.837
-(dings)
-And, please remember,

498
00:40:23.963 --> 00:40:26.757
we have left nothing to chance.

499
00:40:29.927 --> 00:40:33.180
-(screaming)
-(shouts in German)

500
00:40:35.266 --> 00:40:38.185
-Get them back!
-MAN: Stand back!

501
00:40:45.901 --> 00:40:48.279
"Now I have a machine gun.

502
00:40:50.239 --> 00:40:53.617
Ho-ho-ho."

503
00:40:55.786 --> 00:40:58.330
A security guard we missed?

504
00:40:58.330 --> 00:41:00.958
They're usually tired, old policemen
growing fat on a pension.

505
00:41:00.958 --> 00:41:03.127
No, no. This is something else.

506
00:41:03.127 --> 00:41:06.088
-WOMAN: Oh, they're gonna kill us!
-(German)

507
00:41:08.799 --> 00:41:13.762
MEN: (speaking German)

508
00:41:13.762 --> 00:41:16.974
-We have to do something, Hans.
-Yes, we do.

509
00:41:16.974 --> 00:41:21.353
We have to tell Karl his brother is dead.
Tell him to come down.

510
00:41:23.147 --> 00:41:24.148
-Karl?
<i>-KARL (on radio): Yeah?</i>

511
00:41:24.148 --> 00:41:26.233
(speaking German)

512
00:41:26.233 --> 00:41:29.195
HANS: Franco, you and Fritz take the body
upstairs and out of sight.

513
00:41:29.195 --> 00:41:31.947
I don't want the hostages
to think too much.

514
00:41:31.947 --> 00:41:33.866
FRITZ: (speaking German)

515
00:42:34.385 --> 00:42:36.262
(shouts)

516
00:42:36.262 --> 00:42:39.014
-I want blood!
-You'll have it.

517
00:42:39.014 --> 00:42:42.226
But let Heinrich plant the detonators
and Theo prepare the vault.

518
00:42:42.226 --> 00:42:44.478
After we call the police,
they'll waste hours trying to negotiate,

519
00:42:44.728 --> 00:42:47.147
and then you can tear the building apart
looking for this man.

520
00:42:47.147 --> 00:42:50.150
But until then, we do not alter the plan.

521
00:42:50.150 --> 00:42:52.820
And if he alters it?

522
00:42:55.447 --> 00:42:57.449
(indistinct)

523
00:42:57.449 --> 00:42:59.410
ELLIS: What do ya think?

524
00:43:01.245 --> 00:43:03.330
Something's wrong.

525
00:43:03.330 --> 00:43:05.374
Cops?

526
00:43:06.875 --> 00:43:07.793
John.

527
00:43:07.793 --> 00:43:10.879
ELLIS: John? Aw, Christ.

528
00:43:10.879 --> 00:43:13.215
He could fuck this whole thing up.
What does he think he's doin'?

529
00:43:13.215 --> 00:43:15.467
-His job.
-Bullshit.

530
00:43:15.759 --> 00:43:17.803
His job's 3,000 miles away.

531
00:43:17.803 --> 00:43:19.930
Without him, we still have a chance.

532
00:43:19.930 --> 00:43:22.433
We might be able to get outta here.

533
00:43:22.433 --> 00:43:25.060
Tell that to Takagi.

534
00:43:48.417 --> 00:43:51.086
Mayday! Mayday! Anyone copying? Channel 9.

535
00:43:51.086 --> 00:43:53.172
<i>Terrorists have seized</i>
<i>the Nakatomi building</i>

536
00:43:53.172 --> 00:43:55.132
<i>and are holding at least</i>
<i>30 people hostage.</i>

537
00:43:55.132 --> 00:43:58.302
I repeat, unknown number
of terrorists, six or more,

538
00:43:58.302 --> 00:44:01.930
armed with automatic weapons
at Nakatomi Plaza, Century City.

539
00:44:01.930 --> 00:44:03.515
Where's the best place to transmit?

540
00:44:03.515 --> 00:44:04.975
<i>McCLANE: Somebody answer me, goddamn it!</i>

541
00:44:04.975 --> 00:44:06.810
The roof! Go! Go!

542
00:44:09.480 --> 00:44:12.066
WOMAN: It's the same address
as that fire signal.

543
00:44:12.066 --> 00:44:13.901
I'll handle it.

544
00:44:16.403 --> 00:44:20.324
Attention, whoever you are. This channel's
reserved for emergency calls only.

545
00:44:20.324 --> 00:44:23.494
<i>McCLANE: No fuckin' shit, lady.</i>
<i>Do I sound like I'm orderin' a pizza?</i>

546
00:44:36.340 --> 00:44:38.467
No one kills him but me.

547
00:44:40.094 --> 00:44:42.262
They have already killed one hostage.

548
00:44:42.262 --> 00:44:45.474
They are fortifying their positions
while you're jerkin' me off on the radio!

549
00:44:45.474 --> 00:44:47.518
<i>McCLANE: Now, send a police backup ASAP!</i>

550
00:44:47.518 --> 00:44:49.895
Sir, I've already told you,
this is a reserved channel.

551
00:44:49.895 --> 00:44:53.524
If this is an emergency call,
dial 911 on your telephone.

552
00:44:53.857 --> 00:44:57.152
Otherwise, I'll have to report
this as an FCC violation.

553
00:44:57.152 --> 00:44:59.947
Fine, report me!
Come the fuck down here and arrest me!

554
00:44:59.947 --> 00:45:02.574
-Just send the police now!
-(machine gun fire)

555
00:45:02.574 --> 00:45:04.201
Ow!

556
00:45:08.122 --> 00:45:10.999
Whoa!

557
00:45:12.334 --> 00:45:14.503
(coughs)

558
00:45:14.503 --> 00:45:17.923
See if there's a black-and-white
that can do a drive-by.

559
00:45:19.425 --> 00:45:22.261
♪♪ (humming)

560
00:45:29.977 --> 00:45:32.062
I thought you guys just ate donuts.

561
00:45:32.062 --> 00:45:34.565
(chuckles) They're for my wife.

562
00:45:34.565 --> 00:45:36.024
Yeah.

563
00:45:37.526 --> 00:45:38.569
She's pregnant.

564
00:45:38.569 --> 00:45:40.195
Yeah.

565
00:45:40.195 --> 00:45:42.072
Bag it.

566
00:45:43.115 --> 00:45:45.117
Big time.

567
00:45:45.117 --> 00:45:47.369
(chuckling)

568
00:45:48.036 --> 00:45:49.329
Thanks.

569
00:45:52.374 --> 00:45:54.626
<i>WOMAN (on radio): Dispatch</i>
<i>to 8-Lincoln-30, over.</i>

570
00:45:54.877 --> 00:45:57.129
This is 8-Lincoln-30.
Come on in, over.

571
00:45:57.129 --> 00:46:01.091
<i>WOMAN: Investigate a code-2</i>
<i>at Nakatomi Plaza, Century City.</i>

572
00:46:01.091 --> 00:46:04.261
8-Lincoln-30 to Dispatch.
I'm on my way.

573
00:46:36.126 --> 00:46:37.544
Christ!

574
00:46:48.639 --> 00:46:50.098
(grunts)

575
00:47:02.319 --> 00:47:04.196
(grunts)

576
00:47:42.693 --> 00:47:44.236
(shouts in German)

577
00:48:03.672 --> 00:48:05.507
Girls.

578
00:48:05.507 --> 00:48:07.134
FRITZ: (speaking German)

579
00:48:20.230 --> 00:48:22.441
Shit. Where the fuck is it?

580
00:48:42.544 --> 00:48:44.546
(metal clangs)

581
00:48:44.546 --> 00:48:45.797
Oh, my God.

582
00:48:53.221 --> 00:48:55.807
-(German)
-HANS: (on radio, speaking German)

583
00:49:00.270 --> 00:49:02.606
(continues in German)

584
00:49:02.606 --> 00:49:05.275
-He's in the elevator shaft.
-(German)

585
00:49:05.275 --> 00:49:08.779
Perfect. The elevators are locked off.
He can't escape.

586
00:49:08.779 --> 00:49:10.447
Just shut him in and come back down.

587
00:49:12.199 --> 00:49:13.241
(grunts)

588
00:49:14.076 --> 00:49:15.661
Oh, fuck.

589
00:49:21.416 --> 00:49:25.712
Karl, the police are probably
on their way already. Karl!

590
00:49:46.608 --> 00:49:47.901
Christ.

591
00:49:53.365 --> 00:49:55.701
I can stall them,
but not if they hear gunshots.

592
00:49:55.701 --> 00:49:57.452
<i>HANS: If you lock him in,</i>
<i>he'll be neutralized--</i>

593
00:49:57.452 --> 00:49:58.370
(switches off)

594
00:49:58.370 --> 00:50:00.163
(grunting)

595
00:50:45.459 --> 00:50:47.419
(panting)

596
00:51:03.560 --> 00:51:06.897
"Come out to the coast.
We'll get together, have a few laughs."

597
00:51:13.945 --> 00:51:16.740
Now I know what a TV dinner feels like.

598
00:51:26.958 --> 00:51:28.418
(German)

599
00:51:46.770 --> 00:51:49.439
(clattering)

600
00:52:24.599 --> 00:52:26.768
(German)

601
00:53:13.607 --> 00:53:15.108
It's about time.

602
00:53:20.947 --> 00:53:23.658
No signs of disturbance, Dispatch.

603
00:53:23.658 --> 00:53:26.870
<i>WOMAN: 8-L-30, roger. Possible crank call.</i>
<i>Check the area again and confirm.</i>

604
00:53:32.667 --> 00:53:35.629
Who's driving this car, Stevie Wonder?

605
00:53:37.756 --> 00:53:39.466
I do see a guard inside.

606
00:53:40.675 --> 00:53:42.093
I'm gonna go in for a closer look.

607
00:53:42.385 --> 00:53:43.720
<i>WOMAN (on radio): 8-L-30, roger.</i>
<i>Use caution.</i>

608
00:53:46.723 --> 00:53:48.099
Eddie?

609
00:53:48.099 --> 00:53:50.769
I had a feeling you'd be callin'.

610
00:54:14.459 --> 00:54:16.670
Good evenin', officer.
What can I do for you?

611
00:54:20.715 --> 00:54:21.925
(German)

612
00:54:28.431 --> 00:54:30.725
EDDIE: We had that false alarm, you know?

613
00:54:30.725 --> 00:54:34.854
Ask me, that goddamn computer sent you out
on another wild goose chase.

614
00:54:34.854 --> 00:54:38.149
They've been chasing bugs in this system
ever since they installed it.

615
00:54:38.400 --> 00:54:42.529
<i>-ANNOUNCER: Notre Dame on top of USC.</i>
-Aw, shit!

616
00:54:42.529 --> 00:54:44.906
Come on. I got 50 bucks
bet on them assholes.

617
00:54:46.700 --> 00:54:50.036
McCLANE: Come on. Come on.
Where's the fucking cavalry?

618
00:54:57.419 --> 00:54:58.962
(yelling)

619
00:55:00.088 --> 00:55:01.798
(German)

620
00:55:01.798 --> 00:55:03.883
(German)

621
00:55:14.019 --> 00:55:16.938
<i>ANNOUNCER: It was good for 52 yards.</i>

622
00:55:16.938 --> 00:55:18.857
You don't mind if I take
a look around, do you?

623
00:55:18.857 --> 00:55:21.026
No, help yourself.

624
00:55:21.026 --> 00:55:22.944
<i>ANNOUNCER: Seven to nothing, Notre Dame.</i>

625
00:55:22.944 --> 00:55:26.114
<i>The Irish driving 74 yards</i>
<i>in eight plays--</i>

626
00:55:29.117 --> 00:55:32.120
This fucking--
Freeze, motherfucker! Drop it!

627
00:55:32.120 --> 00:55:34.622
-Don't! Don't!
-Put that fucking gun down! Gun down!

628
00:55:34.622 --> 00:55:37.167
-Okay! Don't shoot!
-Drop the fucking gun!

629
00:55:37.167 --> 00:55:38.835
Marco, duck!

630
00:55:43.256 --> 00:55:46.051
MARCO: (shouting in German)

631
00:55:55.518 --> 00:55:57.062
Aw, the hell with this.

632
00:55:58.563 --> 00:56:00.065
(shouting in German)

633
00:56:05.528 --> 00:56:08.156
You are done!

634
00:56:08.156 --> 00:56:11.201
No more table.
Where are you going, pal?

635
00:56:11.534 --> 00:56:15.663
Next time you have a chance
to kill someone, don't hesitate.

636
00:56:23.004 --> 00:56:25.048
Thanks for the advice.

637
00:56:25.048 --> 00:56:26.966
Sorry to waste your time.

638
00:56:26.966 --> 00:56:29.010
No problem at all.

639
00:56:29.010 --> 00:56:30.220
Merry Christmas.

640
00:56:30.220 --> 00:56:31.554
Merry Christmas to you.

641
00:56:36.935 --> 00:56:41.106
<i>♪ Oh, the weather outside is frightful ♪</i>

642
00:56:41.106 --> 00:56:43.233
<i>♪ Dum-dee-dum delightful ♪</i>

643
00:56:45.819 --> 00:56:47.570
Oh, for the love of--

644
00:56:51.282 --> 00:56:54.202
-8-Lincoln-30 to Dispatch.
<i>-WOMAN: 8-L-30, go ahead.</i>

645
00:56:54.202 --> 00:56:56.788
Yeah, that's a wild goose chase
over here at Nakatomi Plaza.

646
00:56:56.788 --> 00:56:59.791
Everything here's okay. Over.

647
00:56:59.791 --> 00:57:03.294
<i>♪ But nobody has no place to go ♪</i>

648
00:57:03.586 --> 00:57:06.589
<i>♪ Let it snow</i>
<i>Let it snow, let it snow ♪</i>

649
00:57:08.591 --> 00:57:11.094
Damn! Goddamn it! Jesus H. Christ!

650
00:57:17.851 --> 00:57:20.103
Welcome to the party, pal!

651
00:57:20.103 --> 00:57:21.896
Goddamn it!

652
00:57:25.066 --> 00:57:28.361
<i>♪♪ (R&B on stereo)</i>

653
00:57:28.361 --> 00:57:30.905
POWELL: Now means now, goddamn it!

654
00:57:30.905 --> 00:57:33.074
Policeman under automatic rifle fire
at Nakatomi!

655
00:57:33.074 --> 00:57:35.076
I need backup assistance now!

656
00:57:36.911 --> 00:57:38.621
Now, goddamn it! Now!

657
00:57:56.222 --> 00:57:58.975
Monica, I can get us a table.

658
00:57:59.767 --> 00:58:01.060
Wolfgang and I are very close friends.

659
00:58:01.060 --> 00:58:03.146
<i>WOMAN (on radio): Officer</i>
<i>in need of assistance.</i>

660
00:58:03.146 --> 00:58:05.148
-I interviewed him.
<i>-WOMAN: Shots fired at Nakatomi.</i>

661
00:58:05.148 --> 00:58:09.152
<i>2000 block, Avenue of the Stars.</i>
<i>Repeat, officer needs assistance at--</i>

662
00:58:09.152 --> 00:58:12.780
<i>POWELL: I'm in Nakatomi Plaza.</i>
<i>They're turning my car into Swiss cheese!</i>

663
00:58:12.780 --> 00:58:16.868
<i>I need backup assistance now!</i>
<i>Now, goddamn it! Now!</i>

664
00:58:16.868 --> 00:58:19.287
(sirens wailing)

665
00:58:37.805 --> 00:58:39.891
I never thought I'd love
to hear that sound.

666
00:58:39.891 --> 00:58:44.354
All of you, relax. This is a matter
of inconvenient timing. That's all.

667
00:58:44.354 --> 00:58:46.439
Police action was inevitable,

668
00:58:46.439 --> 00:58:49.442
and, as it happens, necessary.

669
00:58:49.442 --> 00:58:53.071
So let them fumble about outside,
and stay calm.

670
00:58:53.071 --> 00:58:55.198
-This is simply the beginning.
-(static on radio)

671
00:58:56.324 --> 00:58:59.786
I thought I told all of you I want
radio silence until further--

672
00:58:59.786 --> 00:59:02.330
Oh, I'm very sorry, Hans.
I didn't get that message.

673
00:59:02.330 --> 00:59:05.917
<i>Maybe you should have</i>
<i>put it on the bulletin board.</i>

674
00:59:05.917 --> 00:59:08.378
I figured since I waxed Tony and Marco
and his friend here,

675
00:59:08.378 --> 00:59:11.214
I figured you and Karl and
Franco might be a little lonely.

676
00:59:11.214 --> 00:59:13.383
So I wanted to give you a call.

677
00:59:13.383 --> 00:59:14.884
KARL: How does he know so much about--

678
00:59:17.220 --> 00:59:19.722
That's very kind of you.

679
00:59:19.722 --> 00:59:23.434
<i>I assume you are</i>
<i>our mysterious party crasher.</i>

680
00:59:23.726 --> 00:59:27.063
You are most troublesome
for a security guard.

681
00:59:27.063 --> 00:59:29.983
(makes buzzer sound)
Sorry, Hans. Wrong guess.

682
00:59:29.983 --> 00:59:33.945
Would you like to go for double jeopardy
where the scores can really change?

683
00:59:38.032 --> 00:59:40.159
Hmm. These are very bad for you.

684
00:59:41.452 --> 00:59:42.495
Who are you then?

685
00:59:42.745 --> 00:59:44.914
Just a fly in the ointment, Hans.

686
00:59:44.914 --> 00:59:46.374
A monkey in the wrench.

687
00:59:46.374 --> 00:59:48.835
A pain in the ass.

688
00:59:51.379 --> 00:59:53.464
-Whoa.
-(static)

689
00:59:53.715 --> 00:59:56.134
Check on all the others.
Don't use the radio.

690
00:59:56.134 --> 00:59:59.387
See if he's lying about Marco,
and find out if anyone else is missing.

691
01:00:04.017 --> 01:00:05.893
Mr. Mystery Guest...

692
01:00:07.395 --> 01:00:08.938
<i>are you still there?</i>

693
01:00:09.856 --> 01:00:11.149
Yeah, I'm still here.

694
01:00:11.149 --> 01:00:13.318
Unless you wanna open
the front door for me.

695
01:00:14.027 --> 01:00:16.195
<i>HANS: No, I'm afraid not.</i>

696
01:00:16.195 --> 01:00:18.865
But you have me at a loss.

697
01:00:18.865 --> 01:00:20.950
You know my name, but who are you?

698
01:00:20.950 --> 01:00:26.122
<i>Just another American who saw</i>
<i>too many movies as a child?</i>

699
01:00:26.122 --> 01:00:30.001
<i>Another orphan of a bankrupt culture</i>
<i>who thinks he's John Wayne?</i>

700
01:00:30.001 --> 01:00:33.004
<i>Rambo? Marshal Dillon?</i>

701
01:00:33.004 --> 01:00:36.174
I was always kind of partial
to Roy Rogers actually.

702
01:00:36.174 --> 01:00:38.217
I really liked those sequined shirts.

703
01:00:38.217 --> 01:00:41.429
Do you really think you have
a chance against us, Mr. Cowboy?

704
01:00:41.429 --> 01:00:43.890
(elevator bell dings)

705
01:00:44.807 --> 01:00:46.476
Yippee-ki-yea, motherfucker.

706
01:00:50.480 --> 01:00:52.940
I can get the jump on everybody
if I get a remote.

707
01:00:52.940 --> 01:00:53.941
<i>I don't have the new pages.</i>

708
01:00:53.941 --> 01:00:57.111
<i>-Where's the Gladden report?</i>
-Harvey, keep your pants on, will you?

709
01:00:57.111 --> 01:00:58.404
Sam, look, I'm begging you.

710
01:00:58.404 --> 01:01:00.948
Simon's at a remote thing with
that Santa sing-along.

711
01:01:00.948 --> 01:01:03.451
-I'll tell him to swing by.
-I'm not sitting on this for Simon!

712
01:01:03.451 --> 01:01:05.536
-I don't wanna hear it!
-This is my story!

713
01:01:05.536 --> 01:01:08.081
-I can't hear you.
-All right, look. I tell you what.

714
01:01:08.081 --> 01:01:11.000
You don't wanna give me a truck,
I'll go and I'll steal a truck.

715
01:01:11.000 --> 01:01:13.503
-Give us a break, Thornburg.
-Eat it, Harvey!

716
01:01:13.503 --> 01:01:17.548
Four, three, two, one.

717
01:01:17.548 --> 01:01:20.051
Harvey, we're on the air.

718
01:01:23.596 --> 01:01:27.558
Good evening. This is Harvey Johnson.

719
01:01:27.558 --> 01:01:31.521
And I'm Gail Wallens, and this
is<i> Nightline News </i>at 10:00.

720
01:01:31.521 --> 01:01:34.524
Our top stories on this Christmas Eve--

721
01:01:34.524 --> 01:01:36.484
Take truck number five
and get out of here.

722
01:01:45.451 --> 01:01:48.996
He wasn't lying about Marco.
He's down on the street.

723
01:01:48.996 --> 01:01:51.207
And the other man was Heinrich.

724
01:01:51.207 --> 01:01:53.000
And his bag is missing.

725
01:01:55.336 --> 01:01:57.422
But he had the detonators.

726
01:02:01.134 --> 01:02:02.468
Theo.

727
01:02:03.428 --> 01:02:06.347
<i>-Theo.</i>
-Yo!

728
01:02:06.347 --> 01:02:08.891
<i>We may have some problems.</i>
<i>How's our schedule?</i>

729
01:02:10.101 --> 01:02:11.936
THEO: Three down, four to go.

730
01:02:11.936 --> 01:02:14.147
Then don't waste time talking to me.

731
01:02:15.314 --> 01:02:18.609
This is Sergeant Al Powell
of the Los Angeles Police Department.

732
01:02:18.901 --> 01:02:21.571
If the person who radioed for help
can hear me on this channel,

733
01:02:21.571 --> 01:02:23.614
<i>acknowledge this transmission.</i>

734
01:02:23.865 --> 01:02:26.576
I say again, if the person
who radioed for help

735
01:02:26.576 --> 01:02:29.579
on this channel can hear me,
acknowledge this transmission.

736
01:02:29.871 --> 01:02:30.538
(sirens wailing)

737
01:02:35.084 --> 01:02:37.545
I read you, Powell.
You the guy in the car?

738
01:02:37.545 --> 01:02:39.589
What's left of him.

739
01:02:39.589 --> 01:02:41.507
<i>Can you identify yourself?</i>

740
01:02:41.507 --> 01:02:43.968
Not now. Maybe later.

741
